> Quinoa isn't actually a grain at all! It's botanically related to spinach and beets.
> We love cooking with this ancient Incan superfood because it's nutritious, hearty,
> and pairs well with so many flavors—especially the tangy ones in our stuffed peppers.

Preheat the #oven{} to 400 degrees. In a #small pot{}, bring @water{1 1/2%cups},
@veggie stock concentrate{1}, and a large pinch of @salt{pinch} to a boil. Once boiling,
add the @quinoa{3/4%cup}, cover, and reduce to a simmer for about
~{20%minutes}, until tender.

Wash and dry all produce. Peel and finely chop the @shallot{1}(peeled and finely chopped).
Mince the @garlic{2%cloves}(minced). Finely chop the @parsley{1/4%ounce}(finely chopped).
Thinly slice the @button mushrooms{4%ounce}(thinly sliced). Halve the
@red bell pepper{2%unit} lengthwise before removing the core, seeds, and white veins.

Drizzle the bell peppers with @olive oil{1%tablespoon} and season with @salt and
@pepper. Roast on a #baking sheet{} ~{10-12%minutes}, until slightly softened.

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add the mushrooms.
Cook, tossing, for ~{4-5%minutes}, until golden brown. Add the shallot and garlic.
Cook ~{2-3%minutes}, until fragrant.

Add @white wine vinegar{1%tablespoon}, a drizzle of @olive oil{}, the quinoa,
and half the parsley to the pan. Cook, tossing, for ~{1%minute}. Taste and season
with @salt and @pepper. Spoon the quinoa into the bell peppers, then return to the
oven ~{5-7%minutes}, until the peppers are very soft.

Serve: Sprinkle the quinoa stuffed peppers with @feta cheese{1/2%cup},
@pepitas{1%ounce}, and the remaining parsley. Enjoy!